<dl id="n43a01j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n43" href="#n43a01j">N43 (VI.B.35)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n43all.htm#n43a01j">appendix 1(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 250 alph / 50 live 25 India / Roman / Arab Chinese</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Neither would there be advantages in cataloguing the two hundred and fifty alphabets which have come into being since prehistoric man scratched his rude pictoographs on the face of cliffs and on fragments of slate or bone. Some fifty of these alphabets have survived, and of these about half are found in India &hellip; The rest are, in the main, variations of three scripts &mdash; Roman, Arabic, and Chinese. <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECSA2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ECSA2"><cite title="source">The Story of the Alphabet</cite></a>, rev. ed. (1913) 226f</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: This page is VI.B.49b-verso, right and left margins</mm> </dd></dl>
